  "notes": "Great Bass pipe in C, derived by uniform geometric scaling from the Pipers' Guild 1930s Treble Pipe in D (tuned variant).\n\nScale factor k = f_treble / f_greatbass = 587.33 Hz (D5) / 130.81 Hz (C3) = 4.490×\nAll spatial dimensions (body length, bore, OD, hole positions, hole diameters, chimney heights) multiplied by 4.490.\n\nKey dimensions:\n  Body length: 1311 mm (≈ 1.31 m)\n  Bore at foot: 83.1 mm, bore at head: 81.7 mm (slight taper preserved)\n  Wall thickness: ≈ 13 mm (scaled from 2.9 mm treble wall)\n  Hole diameters: 33.7–35.9 mm front holes, 22.5 mm thumb vent\n  Chimney height: 13.0 mm (all holes)\n\nThe diatonic scale shifts from D major (treble) to C major (great bass), two octaves lower:\n  Treble:    D5  E5  F#5  G5  A5  B5  C#6  D6\n  Great Bass: C3  D3  E3   F3  G3  A3  B3   C4\nNote that the major-second transposition (D→C) removes the two sharps, giving a natural C major scale.\n\nThe bore-to-hole-diameter ratio is preserved exactly from the treble (holes ≈ 40–43% of bore diameter). The very large hole sizes (34–36 mm) reflect a direct acoustic scaling and are consistent with the model physics, but in practice a real instrument at this scale would likely use smaller covered-pad keys or levers rather than direct finger holes. Treat these as acoustically consistent starting dimensions; practical construction may require reducing hole sizes and compensating with chimney adjustments.\n\nThe all-closed fundamental C3 at 1311 mm is predicted by the half-wave formula at 20°C/A440: L = c/(2f) = 343200/(2×130.81) = 1311.6 mm."
